elements.description: Category

The construct C is an internal category in D if given
two objects C0 and C1 in D, respectively the objects
and morphisms of C, if the following diagrams commute.
Map objects to their identity morphism
Internal Definition

Form the pullbacks of objects and morphisms
and lift to the pullback assembly of composable
pairs of identities and morphisms.

Form the pullback of composable morphisms
where the first's codomain equals the second's
domain.

The composite of two morphisms can now be
expressed with the pullback object above as
the domain of the composition morphism.

The domain of the composite is the domain
of the first morphism:  dom(A→B→C) = A

The codomain of the composite is the codomain
of the latter morphism:  cod(A→B→C) = C

The codomain of the identity morphism of an object is
that object itself.

The domain of the identity morphism of an object is
that object itself.

We have the morphisms needed to state
the associative law for composition of
morphisms: (A→B→C)→D = A→(B→C→D)
Let D be a category.
Morphisms have a domain and a codomain.

Now require that the composite of the
identity 1:A→A with any f:A→B is f, and
the composite of any g:C→A with
1:A→A is g.

Form the pullback of the composable
triples in the form (A→B→C)→D.

Form the lift from the composable triple
(A→B→C)→D to the composable pair B→C→D.

Form the lift from the composable triple
(A→B→C)→D to the composable triple A→(B→C→D).

Form the lift from the composable triple
(A→B→C)→D to the composable pair A→C→D.

Form the lift from the composable triple
A→(B→C→D) to the composable pair A→B→D.
